Discover cryptography used in modern networks

In this activity, I explored how cryptography is used in modern networks to secure communication and protect data.

1. WPA2/WPA3 Wi-Fi encryption  
I explored how Wi-Fi networks use WPA2 or WPA3 to encrypt wireless communication. At UWA, I learned that the network uses WPA2/WPA3 with 802.1X authentication. This ensures that data transmitted over Wi-Fi is encrypted and only authorised users can connect.

2. TLS protocol in network communication  
I explored how the TLS protocol is used to encrypt data transmitted over networks. TLS ensures that data exchanged between devices is secure and cannot be easily intercepted by attackers.

3. VPN encryption  
I explored how VPN services use encryption to protect internet traffic. When using a VPN, my data is encrypted before being transmitted over the network, which helps protect it from interception, especially on public Wi-Fi.

Overall, this activity shows that cryptography is essential in modern networks to ensure confidentiality, integrity, and secure communication.
